53. By the disposition os anyels. Greek, “at the appointment of angels,” that is, angels in the name of God ordaining and enjoin- ing the observation of the law. So the law is said to have been ordained by angels, Gal. iii. 19. And, Heb. ii. 2, it is called the word spoken by angels. And although the law was given principally by one angel sustaining the name and person of God, yet because this was done in a stately manner, many troops of angels having attended him as apparitors, the promulgation of the law in Mount Sina is rightly ascribed to angels.
